%S A398043 0,1,10,2,20,3,30,4,40,5,50,6,60,7,70,8,80,9,90,100,11,200,12,300,13,
%T A398043 400,14,500,15,600,16,700,17,800,18,900,19,1000,21,1100,22,1200,23,
%U A398043 1300,24,1400,25,1500,26,1600,27,1700,28,1800,29,1900,31,2000,32
%N A398043 Lexicographically earliest sequence of distinct nonnegative integers such that two consecutive terms have no nonzero digits together at the same position.
%C A398043 A variant of A109812 for the decimal base.
%C A398043 This sequence is a permutation of the nonnegative integers (with inverse A398044):
%C A398043 - the first positive terms with k or more decimal digits is 10^k,
%C A398043 - all powers of 10 appear in the sequence,
%C A398043 - the next term after 10^k is necessarily the least value < 10^k not yet in the sequence if any.
%H A398043 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A398043/b398043.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A398043 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A398043/a398043.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%H A398043 <a href="/index/Per#IntegerPermutation">Index entries for sequences that are permutations of the natural numbers</a>
%F A398043 A344511(a(n)) AND A344511(a(n+1)) = 0 (where AND denotes the bitwise AND operator).
%e A398043 The first terms are:
%e A398043   n   a(n)
